"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapters 11–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-11-12.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/matthew.json (pre-existing: 11:5, 11:28)

Key decisions in this range:
- John the Baptist as Elijah (11:14): classified as direct fulfillment — Jesus makes the
  identification explicitly (see also 17:10-13)
- 11:27 ("no one knows the Father except the Son"): classified as direct revelation —
  the highest Christological self-disclosure in the Synoptic tradition
- 11:25-30 (Yoke passage): classified as direct revelation and fulfillment of Wisdom
  tradition (Wis 6:12-16; Sir 51:23-27) — Jesus as the embodiment of divine Wisdom
- Sabbath controversies (12:1-14): classified as direct revelation — "something greater
  than the temple is here" and "the Son of Man is lord of the Sabbath"
- Sign of Jonah (12:39-40): classified as direct — the most explicit resurrection
  prediction to the hostile audience; three days and three nights
- Blasphemy against the Spirit (12:31-32): classified as direct — Christ makes the
  Spirit's work through him the measure of the unforgivable sin
- New family (12:46-50): classified as revelation of God — the redefinition of family
  around the will of the Father anticipates the new covenant community
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "When Jesus had finished instructing his twelve disciples, he went on from there to teach and preach in their cities." The transition from commissioning to continuing ministry shows Christ\'s mission as both delegating and inexhaustible. The disciples go out; Jesus continues independently. He does not cease his own work when extending it through others — a pattern that anticipates the church\'s mission as extending Christ\'s presence, not replacing it.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now when John heard in prison about the deeds of Christ, he sent word by his disciples." John the Baptist, imprisoned by Herod Antipas, hears reports of Jesus\' ministry. The one who announced the Coming One now sends to ask if that announcement has been fulfilled. John\'s question (v.3) is not doubt but the theological inquiry of one who has risked everything on his proclamation — seeking verification in the face of circumstances (his imprisonment, Jesus\' non-political ministry) that did not match conventional messianic expectation.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "And said to him, \'Are you the one who is to come, or shall we look for another?\'" The "one who is to come" (<em>ho erchomenos</em>) is a messianic title drawn from Ps 118:26 ("Blessed is he who comes in the name of the LORD") and the prophetic expectation of a coming deliverer. John is asking whether the Isaianic fulfillment-signs he observes in Jesus\' ministry match the one he announced. Jesus\' answer (vv. 4-5) does not directly say "yes" but cites the Isaianic signs that only the Messiah performs.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And Jesus answered them, \'Go and tell John what you hear and see.\'" The instruction to "go and tell" what is observed is a deliberate evocation of the prophetic pattern: YHWH\'s acts are to be proclaimed (Ps 66:16; 107:22; Isa 12:4). Jesus points to evidence rather than assertion — his answer to the messianic question is the catalog of his works. The Christological weight: only the Messiah performs these specific signs, and the signs themselves are the answer.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "And blessed is the one who is not offended by me." The beatitude placed at the end of the messianic sign-list is a Christological warning: the signs are sufficient evidence, but they can be resisted. The "offense" (<em>skandalon</em>) of Christ is the scandal of the cross and the unexpectedness of the messianic path. The blessing is for those who persist in faith despite the offense — a category that includes John himself, waiting in prison, and all who follow Christ through suffering.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "As they went away, Jesus began to speak to the crowds concerning John: \'What did you go out into the wilderness to see? A reed shaken by the wind?\'" The rhetorical questions about John establish his identity by negation: not a reed, not a soft-clothing man, but a prophet. The wilderness context recalls both the Exodus (Israel in the desert) and Elijah (the prophet who retreated to the wilderness). John occupies the wilderness as the figure who bridges the prophetic era and the messianic fulfillment.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "What then did you go out to see? A man dressed in soft clothing? Behold, those who wear soft clothing are in kings\' houses." The contrast between the wilderness prophet and the palace courtier defines John\'s role: he stands outside the power structures of his time in order to speak against them (3:7-12; 14:4). The Christological bearing: John\'s ministry is the type of the prophetic tradition that prepared for Christ — uncompromising, outside the establishment, and ultimately silenced by that establishment.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "What then did you go out to see? A prophet? Yes, I tell you, and more than a prophet." Jesus\' affirmation of John as "more than a prophet" positions John at the summit of the prophetic tradition — the one who does not merely point forward from a distance but stands at the threshold and announces the one who is already present. The "more than" (<em>perissoteron</em>) is a comparative that implies a category: John is the last and greatest of the prophets because he is the immediate herald of the fulfillment.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "This is he of whom it is written: \'Behold, I send my messenger before your face, who will prepare your way before you.\'" The citation of Mal 3:1 (conflated with Exod 23:20) is Jesus\' explicit identification of John as the fulfillment of Malachi\'s "messenger" prophecy. The "your way" — addressed to the LORD in Malachi — is now addressed to Jesus: Jesus is the LORD whose way John prepares. The citation is a direct Christological claim: the one before whom John prepares the way is YHWH himself, coming in Jesus.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "Truly, I say to you, among those born of women there has arisen no one greater than John the Baptist. Yet the one who is least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than he." The superlative of John\'s greatness — unmatched among all who have been born — is immediately surpassed by the least kingdom-member. This does not demean John but reveals the qualitative difference between the era of anticipation and the era of fulfillment: the least who stands on the resurrection side of the cross has received what John could only await.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "From the days of John the Baptist until now the kingdom of heaven has suffered violence, and the violent take it by force." The difficult saying about the kingdom and violence has two main interpretations: either violent opponents are trying to seize or suppress the kingdom, or zealous ones are pressing into it with urgency. In either case, the arrival of the kingdom is presented as creating an eschatological pressure — the kingdom\'s presence generates both opposition and urgency. Christ is the king whose arrival creates this crisis.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "For all the Prophets and the Law prophesied until John." The entire prophetic corpus — "all the Prophets and the Law" — is characterized as forward-pointing prophecy, with John marking the end of that era. The Law and Prophets as prophetic anticipation of Christ is Paul\'s thesis in Romans and Galatians; here Jesus states it directly. Everything from Genesis to Malachi was pointing toward the one who has now arrived.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And if you are willing to accept it, he is Elijah who is to come." The identification of John as the promised Elijah of Mal 4:5-6 is made conditional — "if you are willing to accept it" — because it requires a reinterpretation of how Elijah\'s return would look. The literal Elijah returning in a chariot of fire was not what happened; John came in the spirit and power of Elijah (Luke 1:17). The Christological bearing: Jesus alone has the authority to identify the fulfillment of the Elijah-prophecy, and his identification requires rethinking the mode of fulfillment.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "He who has ears to hear, let him hear." The call to discerning hearing — recurring throughout Matthew (13:9, 43) and the Apocalypse (Rev 2:7, 11, etc.) — addresses the gap between hearing and understanding. The Christological bearing: the revelation being offered (the identity of John, the nature of Jesus\' messiahship) is available to those who receive it with faith, but it requires a particular posture of openness. The one who speaks is the one who alone can open ears (Isa 35:5; Ps 40:6).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "But to what shall I compare this generation? It is like children sitting in the marketplaces and calling to their playmates." The children\'s game analogy — playing funeral and playing wedding, dissatisfied with both — describes the generation\'s rejection of both John (too austere) and Jesus (too festive). Both the ascetic herald and the banqueting bridegroom are refused. The Christological point: the generation\'s response to Jesus is not a failure to receive the right messenger but a posture of prior rejection — nothing will satisfy.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'We played the flute for you, and you did not dance; we sang a dirge, and you did not mourn.\'" The complaint of the children in the parable identifies the two modes of reception: joy (wedding) and grief (mourning). John invited mourning-repentance; Jesus invited feast-joy. Both invitations were refused. The Christological irony: the one who embodies both roles — bridegroom and suffering servant — is rejected in both. The generation cannot accept the kingdom because they reject the king, whatever form his arrival takes.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "For John came neither eating nor drinking, and they say, \'He has a demon.\'" John\'s ascetic lifestyle — wilderness diet, no wine — matched the mourning-prophet profile; his generation dismissed him as demonized. The external judgment of John mirrors the coming judgment of Jesus (v.19). Both are rejected by the same generation on opposite grounds: John is too extreme; Jesus is too permissive. The gospel\'s challenge cannot be met by those who have pre-decided their rejection.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct revelation: "The Son of Man came eating and drinking, and they say, \'Look at him! A glutton and a drunkard, a friend of tax collectors and sinners!\' Yet wisdom is justified by her deeds." The "Son of Man came" formula is the mission-arrival language of 9:13 and 10:34, now applied to the Son of Man\'s practice of open table fellowship. The charge of gluttony and drunkenness against Jesus echoes the accusation against the rebellious son in Deut 21:20 — a capital offense. "Wisdom is justified by her deeds" identifies Jesus as the divine Wisdom who vindicates herself through what she accomplishes, not through the approval of her critics.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then he began to denounce the cities where most of his mighty works had been done, because they did not repent." The denunciation of Chorazin, Bethsaida, and Capernaum is the inverse of the commissioning of the twelve: those who receive the kingdom\'s signs and do not repent face eschatological judgment. Christ pronounces this judgment with the same authority he displayed in the beatitudes and in the "I came" sayings. The Christological point: the one who heals and teaches is also the one who judges, and the judgment is proportional to the witness received.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "Woe to you, Chorazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida! For if the mighty works done in you had been done in Tyre and Sidon, they would have repented long ago in sackcloth and ashes." The comparison with Tyre and Sidon — pagan cities denounced by the prophets (Isa 23; Ezek 26-28; Joel 3:4-8) — positions the Galilean towns\' rejection of Jesus as worse than pagan idolatry and violence. To have witnessed the signs of the kingdom in person and refuse them is the greatest possible rejection. The woe-formula echoes the prophetic oracles against the nations.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "But I tell you, it will be more bearable on the day of judgment for Tyre and Sidon than for you." The eschatological judgment Christ pronounces is graded by the privilege of witness: greater revelation incurs greater responsibility. The Christological authority: Christ alone has the standing to calibrate eschatological outcomes, placing himself in the position of the eschatological judge (cf. 25:31-46). The "day of judgment" is a fixed point in his framework, and its outcomes are known to him now.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "And you, Capernaum, will you be exalted to heaven? You will be brought down to Hades. For if the mighty works done in you had been done in Sodom, it would have remained until this day." The Capernaum oracle echoes the Babylon oracle of Isa 14:13-15 ("You said in your heart, \'I will ascend to heaven\'... but you are brought down to Sheol"). The city that hosted Jesus\' Galilean ministry — where the most healings and teachings occurred — receives the sharpest condemnation. The exaltation/humiliation pattern is the eschatological reversal that runs throughout the Gospel (20:16; 23:12).</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "But I tell you that it will be more tolerable on the day of judgment for the land of Sodom than for you." Sodom — the paradigmatic place of divine judgment (Gen 19) — is given lesser condemnation than Capernaum in Jesus\' eschatological calculus. The principle of graduated judgment based on received witness is applied to the city that received the most. The Christological authority again: Christ alone can compare the fates of ancient cities and contemporary towns on the day of judgment, because he is the judge.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "At that time Jesus declared, \'I thank you, Father, Lord of heaven and earth, that you have hidden these things from the wise and understanding and revealed them to little children.\'" The thanksgiving prayer is addressed to the Father as "Lord of heaven and earth" — the creator God. Jesus\' prayer reveals his unique filial relationship: he thanks the Father as the one who has orchestrated the hiddenness and revelation of the kingdom. The reversal (hidden from the wise, revealed to the simple) is the eschatological subversion that characterizes the kingdom throughout (5:3-11).</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "Yes, Father, for such was your gracious will." The prayer of submission — "yes, Father, for so it seemed good to you" (<em>eudokia</em>, good pleasure) — echoes the language of the servant songs (Isa 42:1: "my servant, in whom my soul delights") and the baptismal voice (3:17: "with him I am well pleased"). Jesus submits his own will to the Father\'s <em>eudokia</em>, positioning himself as the one who embodies perfect covenant fidelity. This is the Gethsemane posture (26:39) enacted in thanksgiving rather than agony.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "All things have been handed over to me by my Father, and no one knows the Son except the Father, and no one knows the Father except the Son and anyone to whom the Son chooses to reveal him." This is the highest Synoptic Christological statement — sometimes called "the Johannine thunderbolt" for its resemblance to John 10:15. The mutual exclusive knowledge (only the Father knows the Son; only the Son knows the Father) places Jesus in a unique ontological relationship with God. The soteriological corollary: knowledge of the Father is available only through the Son\'s chosen revelation. This is Christ\'s own claim to be the unique mediator (1 Tim 2:5).</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "Take my yoke upon you, and learn from me, for I am gentle and lowly in heart, and you will find rest for your souls." The yoke of Christ is a direct claim to be the teacher whose instruction replaces all other burdens. The "rest for your souls" echoes Jer 6:16 ("ask for the ancient paths... and you will find rest for your souls") — the prophetic invitation to covenant faithfulness. Jesus presents himself as the fulfillment of that invitation: his yoke is the way of the Father that Jeremiah\'s listeners rejected. The "gentle and lowly" self-description anticipates the Servant of Isa 53:2-3 and the triumphal entry on a donkey (21:5).</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct revelation: "For my yoke is easy, and my burden is light." The contrast with the Pharisees\' burdens (23:4: "they tie up heavy burdens, hard to bear") positions Jesus\' teaching as liberation rather than additional obligation. The "easy" yoke is not effortless discipleship but discipleship rightly ordered — aligned with the Father\'s will rather than human elaboration. The Christological inversion: the one who carries the weight of all human sin (Isa 53:4-6) offers lightness to those who take his yoke, because he has already borne what would otherwise crush them.'
  },
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "At that time Jesus went through the grainfields on the Sabbath. His disciples were hungry, and they began to pluck heads of grain and to eat." The Sabbath controversy opens ch. 12 as Jesus\' authority over the Sabbath is challenged. The Christological claim at the heart of these disputes: the Sabbath was given by YHWH as the sign of the Mosaic covenant (Exod 31:13-17); Jesus\' claim to be Lord of the Sabbath (v.8) is a direct claim to be YHWH, the one who instituted it.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "But when the Pharisees saw it, they said to him, \'Look, your disciples are doing what is not lawful to do on the Sabbath.\'" The Pharisees\' challenge represents the oral law elaboration of Sabbath observance that had extended the biblical prohibition to include gleaning. Jesus will not dispute the purity of their concern but will use two OT precedents to show that the Sabbath was never meant to prohibit necessity-driven action, and that the eschatological presence he embodies supersedes the Sabbath economy.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said to them, \'Have you not read what David did when he was hungry, and those who were with him.\'?" The David precedent — eating the bread of the Presence (1 Sam 21:1-6) — grounds Jesus\' defense in royal and priestly authority. David, as God\'s anointed king, acted outside normal ritual law in a moment of necessity, and was not condemned for it. The Christological argument: if David as anointed king could supersede the bread-of-the-Presence law by necessity, how much more can the Son of David and Son of God determine the application of Sabbath law?</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation: "How he entered the house of God and ate the bread of the Presence, which it was not lawful for him to eat nor for those who were with him, but only for the priests?" The Davidic precedent establishes that Israel\'s greatest king exercised a kind of royal priestly authority in a crisis. Jesus is both greater David and greater priest — the one who combines both offices in himself (Heb 4:14-5:10). His authority over the Sabbath law flows from who he is, not from an arbitrary exemption.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "Or have you not read in the Law how on the Sabbath the priests in the temple profane the Sabbath and are guiltless?" The priestly exception — temple service on the Sabbath involves "work" that is not condemned — establishes that Sabbath observance is relative to the temple\'s claims. The priests serve the temple on the Sabbath without violation. The argument moves to v.6: something greater than the temple is here. If the temple justifies its priests\' Sabbath work, the one who is greater than the temple certainly justifies his disciples\'.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "I tell you, something greater than the temple is here." The comparative "greater than the temple" (<em>meizon</em>) is one of Matthew\'s three "greater than" statements in this section (also vv. 41, 42: greater than Jonah, greater than Solomon). Each comparison identifies Jesus as surpassing Israel\'s greatest institution or figure. The temple was YHWH\'s dwelling place on earth; if something greater than the temple is present, it can only mean that YHWH himself has arrived in a more direct form than the temple embodied. This is the Incarnation stated through comparative Christology.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: "And if you had known what this means, \'I desire mercy, and not sacrifice,\' you would not have condemned the guiltless." The second citation of Hos 6:6 (see 9:13) places Jesus\' own authority on the side of divine mercy against ritual correctness. Those who condemned the disciples for gleaning have misread both Hosea and the situation: the guiltless (<em>anaitios</em>) are those who act in the presence of the one whose presence redefines what is required. The Christological bearing: Christ is the one whose presence creates a new context for all religious obligations.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "For the Son of Man is lord of the Sabbath." The explicit claim "the Son of Man is lord of the Sabbath" is the most direct statement of divine authority in the Sabbath controversies. YHWH created the Sabbath (Gen 2:2-3; Exod 20:11) and commanded it as his own institution. To be "lord of the Sabbath" is to be its author and sustainer — a claim to the identity of the Creator. The Danielic Son of Man who receives authority over all things (Dan 7:13-14) is now identified as the lord of the institution by which Israel marks its covenant with the Creator.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "He went on from there and entered their synagogue." The synagogue confrontation that follows (the withered hand) escalates the Sabbath controversy from a field dispute to a formal synagogue setting. The Christological pattern: Jesus consistently meets opposition in its own territory (synagogues, the temple) rather than avoiding it. He enters the space of confrontation as the one who has authority over it, not as a guest who defers to the host\'s rules.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "And a man was there with a withered hand. And they asked him, \'Is it lawful to heal on the Sabbath?\' — so that they might accuse him." The question is a trap: healing would incur a Sabbath violation charge; not healing would expose apparent callousness. Jesus\' response (v.11-12) turns the question back on the questioners with a sheep-in-a-pit argument, then acts. The Christological significance: Jesus does not debate his way around the question but acts from his own authority, demonstrating that the Lord of the Sabbath can define what the Sabbath permits.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "He said to them, \'Which one of you who has a sheep, if it falls into a pit on the Sabbath, will not take hold of it and lift it out?\'" The sheep-in-a-pit argument appeals to common practice: everyone would rescue an animal on the Sabbath. The argument from the lesser (an animal) to the greater (a man) is standard Jewish legal reasoning. The Christological frame: the one who poses the argument is the same one who will soon say "I am the good shepherd" (John 10:11) — the one who rescues the sheep at any cost, including on the Sabbath.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "Of how much more value is a man than a sheep! So it is lawful to do good on the Sabbath." The principle — doing good on the Sabbath is lawful — summarizes the Sabbath\'s positive intention. The Sabbath was given for life (Ezek 20:11-12), not as a restraint on it. Christ interprets the Sabbath in the direction of its original purpose: the day of God\'s rest that celebrates creation is the appropriate day for the restoration of a human being to full function. Creation\'s completion and re-creation are both Sabbath-logic.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then he said to the man, \'Stretch out your hand.\' And the man stretched it out, and it was restored, healthy like the other." The healing command — addressed to the man, requiring his participation (he stretches out the withered hand) — and the immediate restoration demonstrate the authority Jesus has just claimed in the synagogue. The withered hand restored "like the other" is a creation-level act: the Lord of the Sabbath restores what the fall corrupted. The sign in the synagogue is larger than a miracle; it is a statement about who Jesus is.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "But the Pharisees went out and conspired against him, how to destroy him." The decision to destroy Jesus follows immediately after the healing — the miracle of restoration answers with a conspiracy of death. This is the pattern of the passion in miniature: the one who gives life is sentenced to death by those who consider his life-giving an offense. The Pharisees\' conspiracy (26:3-4: the chief priests and elders conspiring to arrest and kill) is anticipated here; the decision to destroy Jesus is made at the midpoint of his ministry.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus, aware of this, withdrew from there. And many followed him, and he healed them all." The withdrawal from the place of danger and the continued healing of all who follow echoes the servant who does not "cry aloud" or "quarrel in the streets" (v.19, Isa 42:2). Jesus does not confront the conspiracy directly but continues his mission in the face of it. The Christological pattern of the Servant is being enacted: the one who heals and does not retaliate, who continues his mission under threat.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he ordered them not to make him known." The instruction to silence continues the messianic-secret pattern. In the context of the conspiracy (v.14), it is also protective: premature public declaration of messianic identity would accelerate the confrontation before the appointed time. The Christological control over the timing of his own revelation is a consistent feature of Matthew\'s Gospel — the disclosure accelerates toward the passion but is managed by Jesus\' own deliberate choices.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "This was to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet Isaiah." The fulfillment formula introduces the longest OT citation in Matthew (Isa 42:1-4), Matthew\'s explicit identification of Jesus as the Servant of YHWH. The citation is placed at exactly the moment when the conspiracy against Jesus begins — the Servant\'s quiet faithfulness is the answer to the hostility of the religious establishment.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "\'Behold, my servant whom I have chosen, my beloved with whom my soul is well pleased. I will put my Spirit upon him, and he will proclaim justice to the Gentiles.\'" The citation of Isa 42:1 echoes the baptismal voice (3:17: "my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased") — the Spirit at the baptism fulfills the Spirit-upon-the-Servant promise. The justice proclaimed to the Gentiles anticipates the Great Commission (28:19). Matthew identifies the Servant as the same one named "Son" at the baptism: the Isaianic Servant is the Son of God.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "He will not quarrel or cry aloud, nor will anyone hear his voice in the streets." The Servant\'s non-confrontational public profile — no street-proclamation, no quarreling — is fulfilled in the withdrawal of v.15 and the instruction to silence of v.16. The Servant\'s power is not exercised through the normal mechanisms of public influence (loud proclamation, social pressure) but through the quiet faithfulness that will eventually bring justice to the nations. The cross will be the ultimate expression of this non-coercive power.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "A bruised reed he will not break, and a smoldering wick he will not quench, until he brings justice to victory." The bruised reed and smoldering wick are images of fragility and near-extinction — those who barely survive in the face of oppression. The Servant\'s ministry is characterized by gentleness toward the fragile: he does not finish off what is nearly broken but restores it. This is the character of the healing ministry in chs. 8-9 (lepers, paralytics, the hemorrhaging woman, the dead daughter) — the most vulnerable are precisely those Jesus restores.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And in his name the Gentiles will hope." The citation of Isa 42:4 ("the coastlands wait for his law") in its LXX form ("in his name the Gentiles will hope") concludes the Servant citation with the universal scope of Christ\'s mission. The hope of the Gentiles (<em>elpizō</em>) is grounded in the name of the Servant-Son — the name above every name (Phil 2:9-11). Matthew places the Gentile hope here, at the midpoint of the Gospel, as the interpretive key to everything that follows: the Servant who is being opposed will become the hope of all nations.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Then a demon-oppressed man who was blind and mute was brought to him, and he healed him, so that the man spoke and saw." The compound miracle — healing both blindness and muteness simultaneously — mirrors the signs of 11:5 (blind see, mute speak) and their Isaianic source (Isa 35:5-6). The immediately preceding Servant citation makes the connection explicit: this is the Servant-Son doing what Isa 42 described. The man\'s restoration to both sight and speech is the comprehensive healing that the Servant\'s presence brings.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "And all the people were amazed, and said, \'Can this be the Son of David?\'" The crowd\'s amazed question — "can this be the Son of David?" — is the messianic recognition that the Pharisees will immediately contest (v.24). The question reflects the popular messianic expectation: the Son of David (2 Sam 7:12-16) was expected to restore Israel\'s glory and defeat its enemies. Jesus performs the messianic signs (healing the blind and mute) while refusing the military-political role, creating a cognitive dissonance that the crowd processes as a question and the leaders process as a threat to be neutralized.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "But when the Pharisees heard it, they said, \'It is only by Beelzebul, the prince of demons, that this man casts out demons.\'" The Beelzebul charge (anticipated in 10:25) is the Pharisees\' counter to the crowd\'s messianic recognition. Unable to deny the power of the miracles, they attribute it to demonic rather than divine origin. This is the specific blasphemy that Jesus will identify as unforgivable (v.31-32): attributing the work of the Holy Spirit to Satan. The Christological import: the dispute is not about technique but about the source of Jesus\' power — and the source is the Spirit of God (v.28).</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "Knowing their thoughts, he said to them, \'Every kingdom divided against itself is laid waste, and no city or house divided against itself will stand.\'" The knowledge of unspoken thoughts (repeated from 9:4) again reveals the divine attribute of heart-knowledge. The divided-kingdom argument is not merely strategic but theologically revealing: Jesus\' exorcisms represent a unified kingdom of God advancing against the kingdom of Satan. The very coherence of his ministry — healing and liberation, not chaos — is evidence of divine origin.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "And if Satan casts out Satan, he is divided against himself. How then will his kingdom stand?" The Beelzebul charge collapses under its own logic: a Satan who casts out Satan has declared war on himself. Jesus exposes the incoherence of the charge not by asserting his own identity but by showing that the premise is self-refuting. The Christological bearing: the systematic liberation Jesus brings is the signature of a kingdom advancing against another — not a kingdom in self-contradiction.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "And if I cast out demons by Beelzebul, by whom do your sons cast them out? Therefore they will be your judges." The Jewish exorcism tradition (referenced here as "your sons") practiced exorcism in YHWH\'s name. If the Pharisees\' disciples\' exorcisms were acceptable, the logic of the Beelzebul charge cannot be applied only to Jesus without inconsistency. The Pharisees\' own practitioners become the refutation of their charge — and the standard by which their inconsistency will be judged.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "But if it is by the Spirit of God that I cast out demons, then the kingdom of God has come upon you." The conditional "if" here is not a real uncertainty but a logical construction: the Spirit of God is the source, and therefore the kingdom has arrived. The statement "the kingdom of God has come upon you" (<em>ephthasen eph\' hymas</em>) uses the aorist of arrival — the kingdom has not merely approached but has landed. The exorcisms are not just signs of the kingdom; they are the kingdom\'s actual presence in Christ by the Spirit. This is the foundational Christological claim of the exorcism controversies.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "Or how can someone enter a strong man\'s house and plunder his goods, unless he first binds the strong man? Then indeed he may plunder his house." The binding of the strong man is the paradigm for the exorcism ministry: Satan is the strong man whose house (the world under his dominion) is being plundered. Jesus\' exorcisms are acts of plunder — liberating what Satan held captive. The binding that enables the plunder is accomplished definitively at the cross (John 12:31: "now the ruler of this world will be cast out") and anticipated in every exorcism.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct revelation: "Whoever is not with me is against me, and whoever does not gather with me scatters." The absolute either/or of alignment with Christ admits no neutral position. The gathering/scattering imagery echoes the shepherd-gathering of Ezek 34 (YHWH gathering his scattered flock) and the harvest metaphor of 9:37-38. Christ is both the gatherer and the one around whom gathering or scattering is determined. There is no third option in relation to him — this is the eschatological demand of his presence.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "Therefore I tell you, every sin and blasphemy will be forgiven people, but the blasphemy against the Spirit will not be forgiven." The declaration that every sin and blasphemy — except one — will be forgiven is a proclamation of the scope of divine mercy before it announces its limit. The one unforgivable sin is not ordinary failure but the specific rejection of the Spirit\'s testimony to Christ. Forgiveness is available for all who come to Christ; it is unavailable to those who, having seen his work by the Spirit, attribute it to Satan — because this closes the very channel through which forgiveness comes.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "And whoever speaks a word against the Son of Man will be forgiven, but whoever speaks against the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven, either in this age or in the age to come." The distinction between speaking against the Son of Man (forgivable — Peter will do this, 26:70-74) and speaking against the Holy Spirit (unforgivable) reflects the different nature of the two rejections. Rejection of the Son of Man in ignorance or weakness can be overcome by repentance; but attributing the Spirit\'s clear work to Satan is a willful closing of oneself to the very means of repentance and forgiveness. The "age to come" language is eschatological: this unforgiveness is permanent.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "Either make the tree good and its fruit good, or make the tree bad and its fruit bad, for the tree is known by its fruit." The tree-fruit metaphor (repeated from 7:17-18) is here directed against the Pharisees: their judgment of Jesus\' ministry is fruit that reveals the tree — either their judgment is correct (which would make them good trees) or their judgment is wrong (which makes them bad trees). The Christological application: the Pharisees\' failure to recognize the Spirit\'s work in Jesus is not a neutral error but a revelation of their spiritual condition.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "You brood of vipers! How can you speak good, when you are evil? For out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaks." The "brood of vipers" accusation (used by John the Baptist in 3:7) is the strongest denunciation in the Gospel. The heart-speech connection identifies the Pharisees\' Beelzebul accusation as a disclosure of their inner condition. The Christological bearing: speech about Christ — whether faithful confession or hostile accusation — reveals the speaker\'s heart. The confession "Jesus is Lord" and the charge "he has Beelzebul" are equally diagnostic of the speaker\'s relation to God.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "The good person out of his good treasure brings forth good, and the evil person out of his evil treasure brings forth evil." The treasure-of-the-heart image anticipates the parable of the hidden treasure (13:44) where the kingdom is the treasure. Here, the treasure is the moral content of the heart from which speech flows. The Christological frame: the good treasure is ultimately the kingdom itself, which is present where Christ is received. The evil treasure is the rejection of the kingdom that the Pharisees\' hearts hold.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: "I tell you, on the day of judgment people will give account for every careless word they speak." The eschatological accountability for "careless" (<em>argon</em>, idle/unfruitful) words extends the judgment principle to speech that seems inconsequential. The Pharisees\' casual attribution of Jesus\' works to Beelzebul is precisely such a "careless" word — a dismissive characterization that carries ultimate weight. Christ pronounces this as the one who will preside at the judgment where these words are rendered as evidence.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: "For by your words you will be justified, and by your words you will be condemned." The justification/condemnation by words is not a works-based reversal of grace but the application of the heart-speech principle to the final judgment. The words that justify are those that confess Christ (10:32: "everyone who acknowledges me before men, I will also acknowledge"); the words that condemn are those that deny or blaspheme him. The criterion is relational: acknowledgment or denial of the one who speaks these words.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then some of the scribes and Pharisees answered him, saying, \'Teacher, we wish to see a sign from you.\'" The request for a sign after the healing of the blind-mute man (v.22) and the Beelzebul controversy reveals the depth of the Pharisees\' unbelief: they have witnessed signs and require yet another. The demand for a sign "from you" implies that they have not accepted the existing signs as sufficient. Jesus\' response (v.39-40) is the sign of Jonah — the only sign that will be given to an evil and adulterous generation.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: "But he answered them, \'An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign, but no sign will be given to it except the sign of the prophet Jonah.\'" The "evil and adulterous generation" (<em>genea ponēra kai moichalis</em>) uses "adulterous" in the prophetic sense of covenant unfaithfulness (Jer 3:6-10; Ezek 16; Hos 2:2-13): Israel as the bride who has played the harlot with other gods. The refusal of another sign redirects attention to the one definitive sign: the death and resurrection of the Son of Man, encoded in Jonah\'s experience.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A direct revelation: "For just as Jonah was three days and three nights in the belly of the great fish, so will the Son of Man be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth." The typology of Jonah is made explicit: Jonah\'s three days in the fish\'s belly is a type of the Son of Man\'s three days in the earth (death and burial). The resurrection — implied but not stated explicitly here — is the sign that vindicates Jesus\' identity to the generation that demanded a sign. They will have received the greatest sign, and the majority will still refuse to believe (28:11-15).</p>',
    "41": '<p>A direct revelation: "The men of Nineveh will rise up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, for they repented at the preaching of Jonah, and behold, something greater than Jonah is here." The second "greater than" statement in this section (cf. v.6, greater than the temple; v.42, greater than Solomon). Jonah was a reluctant prophet who brought a brief word of judgment; the Ninevites repented. Jesus brings the full revelation of the kingdom. If pagan Ninevites repented at less, this generation\'s refusal at more is indefensible. The "greater than Jonah" is a transparent claim to surpass the entire prophetic tradition.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct revelation: "The queen of the South will rise up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, for she came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Solomon, and behold, something greater than Solomon is here." The third "greater than" claim: greater than temple, greater than Jonah, greater than Solomon. Solomon was Israel\'s greatest king, the builder of the temple, the embodiment of divine wisdom (1 Kgs 3:12; 4:29-34). The Queen of Sheba came from the ends of the earth for Solomon\'s wisdom. Jesus claims to surpass Solomon — to be the Wisdom of God in person (1 Cor 1:24, 30). The claim is comprehensive: greater than every institution and figure in Israel\'s history.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A revelation of God: "When the unclean spirit has gone out of a person, it passes through waterless places seeking rest, but finds none." The parable of the returning demon applies directly to the Pharisees\' generation. An exorcism that is not followed by genuine occupation of the divine presence creates a worse emptiness. The Christological bearing: the kingdom has come in the person of Christ; those who reject him after his exorcistic work leaves not an empty house but one ready for worse occupation. The sign-demanding Pharisees exemplify the danger of experiencing the kingdom\'s power while refusing the King.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then it says, \'I will return to my house from which I came.\' And when it comes, it finds the house empty, swept, and put in order." The "empty" house is the key: the house is cleaned but not occupied by the divine presence. The Christological application: only the presence of Christ fills the space left by exorcism; the kingdom cannot be received in part — the exorcism without the King leaves a dangerous vacancy. This is the pastoral warning embedded in the Christological narrative: receiving the signs of the kingdom without receiving the King is not a stable intermediate position.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then it goes and brings with it seven other spirits more evil than itself, and they enter and dwell there, and the last state of that person is worse than the first. So also will it be with this evil generation." The application to "this evil generation" makes the parable explicitly generational: the nation that experiences the kingdom\'s power in Jesus\' ministry and refuses him is setting itself up for a worse condition than before. This is the prophetic warning that finds its historical fulfillment in 70 CE (the destruction of Jerusalem, 24:1-28). The "last state worse than the first" is the eschatological judgment on covenant unfaithfulness.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A revelation of God: "While he was still speaking to the people, behold, his mother and his brothers stood outside, asking to speak to him." The arrival of Jesus\' biological family during his teaching creates the occasion for the redefinition of family in v.48-50. The family\'s standing "outside" (<em>exō</em>) while Jesus teaches "inside" is both physical description and symbolic foreshadowing: the family defined by biology stands at the margin of the community defined by obedience to the Father.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A revelation of God: "Someone told him, \'Your mother and your brothers are standing outside, asking to speak to you.\'" The announcement of the family\'s presence is the hinge on which the redefinition of family turns. The Christological significance of the interruption: Jesus does not leave his teaching to attend to biological family obligation — the call of the kingdom, the gathering of disciples, has priority over the claim of natural family (cf. 10:37: "whoever loves father or mother more than me is not worthy of me").</p>',
    "48": '<p>A direct revelation: "But he replied to the man who told him, \'Who is my mother, and who are my brothers?\'" The rhetorical question does not deny his biological family but relativizes it in light of a more fundamental relationship. The Christological bearing: Jesus is redefining the family of God around himself — those who are gathered around him in obedience to the Father constitute the new covenant community. The question prepares the answer that will define the church\'s self-understanding.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A direct revelation: "And stretching out his hand toward his disciples, he said, \'Here are my mother and my brothers!\'" The gesture — hand stretched toward the disciples — is an act of identification and inclusion. The disciples, gathered around him in his teaching, are identified as the family of Christ. The Christological claim is also an ecclesiological one: the community formed around Jesus\' teaching is the family of the Son of God, and therefore (by the adoption logic of Paul, Rom 8:14-17) the children of the Father.</p>',
    "50": '<p>A direct revelation: "For whoever does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother and sister and mother." The definition of the new family — doing the will of the Father — is simultaneously the definition of discipleship and the criterion of belonging. "My Father in heaven" is the filial language Jesus uses exclusively for his own relationship to God; those who do the Father\'s will are brought into the same family relationship. The Christological resolution: to be in Christ\'s family is to share his relation to the Father. This is the adoption logic of the NT (John 1:12; Rom 8:15-16; Gal 4:4-7) stated by Jesus himself.</p>'
  }
}

